# Introduction

A tool for wireframing role-playing games.

Wireframer is an engine-agnostic tool for script-first RPG design. With this, you can write locations, NPC dialogue, interactive items, and relationships between all these; test everything works as intended; and then export to a format ready to be used directly with the game engine and assets. It's designed for iterative development: if you change your mind during level-building, it's easy to edit the game's script within Wireframer. For example, if during development you change your mind between a 2D side-scroller and top-down 2D, the same scripts should work for both, the changes necessary should all relate to the engine and visual assets.

# Installation

For the text runner only:

`pip install pyyaml inkpython`

`python runners/text.py`

For the visual runner:

`pip install pygame`

`python runners/visual.py`

# Directory structure

world/
  rooms/         ← YAML, engine-agnostic forever
  npcs/          ← schedules, stats, flags
  items/
  pc.yaml
dialogue/        ← .ink files, also engine-agnostic
assets/
  portraits/     ← referenced by NPC name, used from layer 2 upward
  maps/          ← referenced by room name, used from layer 2 upward
  sprites/       ← used from layer 3 upward
runners/
  text.py          ← Python, ~300 lines
  visual.py        ← Python + pygame or similar, ~500 lines
  export/
    godot/
    rpgmaker/

# NPCs

These should be YAML files. The following are keywords:

accosts = False: If True, they talk to you as soon as you enter an area. Useful for enemies or shopkeepers.
guards-exits = []: A list of exits. If you try to use the exit, this NPC will accost you and prevent it. Useful for doorkeepers.
guards-items = []: A list of items. If you try to take the item, this NPC will accost you and prevent it.
name = "": Their display name.
description = "": A description. This is used in text mode only, not exported, but it's good practice to document.
portrait = {filename without .yaml}.png: Their default portrait. Recommended to use filename-happy.png, etc.
location: Where they spawn into the world. You can pass a list for characters that might want to be in multiple locations at once, eg generic shopkeepers or enemies where you can't be bothered spawning unique NPCs.
inventory = []: A list of items. You might use inventory to store other game objects you might collect such as skills: you might not in your final game, but it can simplify your code for the wireframe.
money = 0.

Additionally, you can set whatever other variables you might want to use in your game, such as hp, gold, inventory, etc, using the same syntax.

## PC

This follows the same structure as an NPC, but has some additional keywords:

spawn = null: Which map to begin the game in.

# External functions

These are functions you're likely to use in a lot of games. Values can be nested, using . notation.

`get("var_name")`: `var_name` some numeric global variable.

Return the variable's value. Only usable for numbers.

`It'll cost you {item.price} gold.`

`get_str("var_name")`: `var_name` some string global variable.

Return the variable's value. Only usable for strings.

`Pleased to meet you, {player.name}!`

`increase("var_name", amount)`: `var_name` some numeric global variable, `amount` numeric. 

Increase a variable by some amount. Set `amount` negative to subtract.

`~ increase(player.gold, item.price)`

`set("var_name", value)`: `var_name` some global variable, `value` some value.

Set a variable to some value.

`~ set("player.hp", get("player.max_hp"))`

`spend(var_name, amount)`: `var_name` some numeric global variable, `amount` numeric > 0.

Check if a variable is higher than some amount and subtract if so and return true, otherwise return false. Useful for buying things.

`{ spend("player.gold", "item.price"):`
`  ~ add("player.inventory", item)`
`    Thank you, please come again.`
`  - else:`
`    You can't afford it.`
`}`

`shop(stock, restock=True, sells=True, buys=False, sell_markup=1, buy_discount = 0.5)`: `stock` a list of object with names and prices, `restock` a boolean for whether it should provide unlimited items as opposed to depleting, `sells` a boolean for whether the shopkeeper sells to the player, `buys` a boolean for whether the shop buys from the player, `sell_markup` a multiplier for how many times an item's price do they charge to buy, `buy_discount` a multiplier for how many times an item's price will they pay for it.

Create a shop dialogue.

` ~ shop("alice.inventory", false)`

`has(list_name, item, amount=1)`: `list_name` some global variable that's a list, `item` an item, `amount` a positive integer.

See if a list contains an item. Can check if it has a certain amount of an item.

`~ has("player.inventory", "gold_piece", 10)`

`add(list_name, item, amount=1)`: `list_name` some global variable that's a list, `item` an item, `amount` a positive integer.

Add an item to a list.

`~ add("player.inventory", item)`

`remove(list_name, item, amount=1)`: `list_name` some global variable that's a list, `item` an item, `amount` a positive integer.

Remove an item (or multiple copies of it) from a list.

`~ remove("player.inventory", "invitation")`

`sell(list_name, item, amount=1)`: `list_name` some global variable that's a list, `item` an item, `amount` a positive integer.

Check if a list contains (some amount of copies of) an item and remove them. Useful for selling things.

`{ sell("player.inventory", gem):`
`  ~ add("player.gold", get("gem.price"))`
`    Thank you, please come again.`
`  - else:`
`    You can't sell what you don't have.`
`}`

`at(npc, map)`: `npc` an NPC hanlde, `map` a map handle.

Check if an NPC is in a map.

`~ at("bob", highway_melbourne_sydney)`

`move(npc, to)`: `npc` an NPC handle, `to` a map handle.

Move an NPC to a map or list of maps.

`~ move("alice", "")` # remove her from game world